ch tenant owns that trigger so I can query the right database when firing. I'm going to create a min-heap module, then refactor the scheduler to use it instead of running DB queries on the hot path, and update the CRUD operations to keep the heap in sync.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to have the scheduler expose methods like `addTrigger`, `removeTrigger`, and `updateTrigger` that the HTTP handlers can call after modifying the database, or I could have the `nudge()` method rebuild just the affected trigger in the heap rather than doing a full refresh. the heap after CRUD operations. The heap entries need to track the trigger ID, tenant ID for multi-tenancy, and the next scheduled time for comparison. On the hot path, I'll peek at the heap to find the earliest trigger, pop any entries that are due, fetch their full data from the database, fire them, compute the next execution time, and push the updated entry back—this eliminates the O(n) scan and makes each trigger fire a single database lookup.\n\nNow I'm implementing this with a min-heap and a lookup index for efficient updates and removals. Building the heap class... I need to add a database function to fetch triggers by their IDs along with persona data, which will be more efficient than scanning the full table when popping due triggers from the heap.\n\nLooking at the existing `getDueTriggersWithPersona` query, I realize it already has an index-friendly structure with the `(enabled, next_trigger_at)` condition, so the real bottleneck might be elsewhere in the `computeNextDelay` function rather than the initial trigger fetch itself.\n\nRegardless, the requirement is to implement a min-heap, so let me move forward with that approach and check what indexes are currently defined on the triggers table.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3149,"cache_read_input_tokens":31380,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_t